Elizabeth Ann Harper John.
Elizabeth Ann Harper John, hence the Elizabeth A.H. John under which I publish.
I was born and reared in a little county seat town, Marika, just across the Red River.
And as an undergraduate history major, I was working for an honors project, honors thesis, at Oklahoma College for Women, which no longer exists under that name.
It's now called Oklahoma University of Sciences and Arts.
And it's co-educational, which I think is a bad move.
But at any rate,
I started trying to document or to explain why every time they plow down in the southeastern corner,
of Jefferson County, and across the river in Montague County, they turned up incredible quantities of the plants, which I now know to be Indian, French, and to a lesser degree, Spanish.
And so I, nobody had ever explained those things, and so I began researching them.
And that led me into this field.
And I discovered that they had been Wichita and Calvias villages.
And so trying to track those Indians and understand what was going on led me into the wonderful world of the Spanish documents.
And starting with that kind of question, there's just never been any answer to that.
So it's just been tremendously rewarding.
